threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32+ executable (console) x86-64, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Identifies StormDNS, a DNS shell used by Storm-260 to receive and execute commands from a C2.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: @bartblaze

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a backdoor that uses DNS tunneling for command and control (C2). It executes arbitrary shell commands by calling `_popen` with `cmd.exe /c %s 2>&1`. It communicates with its C2 by sending and receiving data via DNS TXT queries to the typo-squatted domain `update.updatemicfosoft.com`. The malware hides its console window using `ShowWindow` to operate stealthily. The PDB path `...\ak47c2\dnsclinet-c\...` further indicates its identity as a malicious tool.
